post_text:
Dear East Orange School District Parents, Guardians, and Caretakers,

After careful review of the district’s parent/guardian survey results, real time data as well as consultation with local agencies and partners, the East Orange School District’s Board of Education, on August 11, 2020, approved the Superintendent’s full remote learning plan for submission to the New Jersey Department of Education. To that end, the remote learning plan for all students will begin on September 8, 2020 pending approval from the New Jersey Department of Education. As it stands, there will no longer be an in-person learning option for students in September.

Full Letter from Superintendent Hasan is attached.....
text:
Dear East Orange School District Parents, Guardians, and Caretakers,

After careful review of the district’s parent/guardian survey results, real time data as well as consultation with local agencies and partners, the East Orange School District’s Board of Education, on August 11, 2020, approved the Superintendent’s full remote learning plan for submission to the New Jersey Department of Education. To that end, the remote learning plan for all students will begin on September 8, 2020 pending approval from the New Jersey Department of Education. As it stands, there will no longer be an in-person learning option for students in September.

Full Letter from Superintendent Hasan is attached.....

Good Evening Parents, and Community Members,

We, the EOSD, need you to know that guidance and orders from Federal, State and Local agencies change weekly, sometimes daily.

Based on this, plans are subject to change.

We are closely monitoring these changes and are conferencing regularly with other Districts to make sure that we are using the most current information when making decisions to ensure the health and safety of our students and staff.

post_text:
The East Orange School District strongly encourage all students who have registered for an AP Exam to proceed with their plans to take it. The district, school administrators and AP teachers are committed to supporting students through the AP Exam process and the district will continue to pay all exam fees.

Because of the COVID-19 pandemic and remote learning, exams will be handled differently this year. The College Board will be providing at home, online exams.

The exam will only include topics and skills most AP teachers and students have already covered in class by early March.

This year's AP Exams will be open book/open note.

Students will be able to take exams on any device they have access to - computer, tablet, or smartphone. They will be able to either type and upload their responses or write responses by hand and submit a photo via their cell phone. For more information, please visit https://apcoronavirusupdates.collegeboard.org/

text:
The East Orange School District strongly encourage all students who have registered for an AP Exam to proceed with their plans to take it. The district, school administrators and AP teachers are committed to supporting students through the AP Exam process and the district will continue to pay all exam fees.

Because of the COVID-19 pandemic and remote learning, exams will be handled differently this year. The College Board will be providing at home, online exams.

The exam will only include topics and skills most AP teachers and students have already covered in class by early March.

This year's AP Exams will be open book/open note.

Students will be able to take exams on any device they have access to - computer, tablet, or smartphone. They will be able to either type and upload their responses or write responses by hand and submit a photo via their cell phone. For more information, please visit https://apcoronavirusupdates.collegeboard.org/

post_text:
The Division of Curriculum Services is launching a Middle School Math Textbook Adoption Showcase on December 10, 2019 before and after the board meeting and from December 13, 2019 through December 20, 2019 at various locations in the district. Please see attached flyer.

As part of the adoption process we kindly ask that all central office staff, building administrators, teachers, parents, and students stop by to look at the various programs that will be considered for our middle school adoption in Fall 2020. You will have the opportunity to submit a rubric that will help us decide on the top 3 - 4 textbook companies that will be invited to participate in the second round of the adoption process in January.

We are confident this initiative will support our efforts to provide all of our middle school students with engaging, meaningful, and effective mathematics resources that are aligned to the NJSLS and Standards for Mathematical Practices.

December is National Impaired Driving Prevention Month. The season between Thanksgiving and New Year’s Day is what the National Association of Drug Court Professionals describe as “one of the deadliest and most dangerous times on America’s roadways due to an increase in impaired driving.” This activity is called “Musical Safety Driving Chairs” this is an engaged activity that helps youth know about the dangers of impaired driving.

This is the second year that ADAPT is having an art contest its for any youth that is in Grades 6-12 that live in Essex County.

post_text:
Friends of Future Ready Prep Present "Oxfam Hunger Banquet".

Hunger Banquets give attendees the opportunity to make a difference, both locally and globally. They are volunteer-led interactive events that bring statistics about poverty to life. Guests randomly select tickets matching real people who are high-, middle-, or low-income earners, demonstrating that where you end up is all in the luck of the draw.

Date: November 19th
Time: 6pm -9pm
Location: Hart Complex Cafeteria (116 Hamilton Street)

This is a free event. Please secure your ticket by clicking on below link!!

https://www.eventbrite.com/e/future-ready-prep-presents-oxfam-hunger-banquet-tickets-79186507977

post_text: In recognition with state requirement for schools in the state of New Jersey to acknowledge the month of October as Anti-Bullying Month, and educate our students on bullying prevention and intervention to give them skills and techniques they can use to resolve conflict at its lowest level, or have the wherewithal to know what to do when faced with a bullying situation. School Resource Officer Epps and Mr. Allen Ashby School Counselor/ABS has partnered together to create Anti-Bullying workshops for students at Cicely L. Tyson Elementary School of Performing & Fine Arts grades 3-5 to educate them with skills and techniques when faced with a bullying conflict. These workshops are held every Friday in 20-minute intervals where Officer Epps and Mr. Ashby engage the students with real life bullying examples that is relevant to today’s students.
